  <h3>Comments</h3>
  <ul class="collections forumthreadposts"><li>
2 comments</li>
<li class=""><span class="comment-number">1. </span><cite>At 20:33 on <span class="date">12 November 2010</span>, <span class="vcard"><span class="fn">Paul R Syms</span></span> wrote:</cite><p class="comment-text">In many ways this is the 'odd one out' of the objects chosen to represent the nineteenth century.  The others show what man was capable of - mass production, exquisite art and printing, fine science and engineering - while this object at best represents Iron Age technology, and a culture that has bypassed the Enlightenment.  No wonder our armies had no qualms about using the newly-invented machine guns against the Mahdi.  (Perhaps the IWM could furnish one of the latter objects for the History of the World gallery?)</p><p class="flag"><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/ahistoryoftheworld/comments/UserComplaintPage?PostID=103004256&amp;amp;s_start=1" class="popup">Complain about this comment</a></p></li>
<li class=""><span class="comment-number">2. </span><cite>At 12:16 on <span class="date">27 December 2010</span>, <span class="vcard"><span class="fn">Nicol_Ash</span></span> wrote:</cite><p class="comment-text">I feel that Paul Syms' comment calls for a bit more historical background.  Chris Spring's note is, of course, well-informed, but he could have added that the black non-Muslim (or only nominally Muslim) soldier-slaves tended to change sides with enthusiasm as soon as the advance of the British-Egyptian-Sudanese forces allowed them to do so.  Some remained  in Mahdist service, but by September 1898 large numbers of black and some Arab Sudanese had been integrated with the existing British-trained Egyptian and Sudanese battalions, on their way south from Egypt, and played a key part in the victory near Omdurman.  The battle was at one point a close-run thing, and not simply a one-sided massacre.  Among Arabs disaffected with the results of  Mahdism were the Ja'alin of the north, who were delighted by Kitchener's defeat of the Emir Mahmoud at the Battle of the Atbara, earlier in '98.   Mahdism led to a highly significant uprising, but it should not be viewed through a modern nationalist  lens.   The ethnic/political complexities are wonderfully illustrated by this drum.</p><p class="flag"><a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/ahistoryoftheworld/comments/UserComplaintPage?PostID=104511413&amp;amp;s_start=1" class="popup">Complain about this comment</a></p></li>
